Subject: [PATCH 0002] Bound fixed-point fractional bits and keep decoded logits finite

Two decode hazards in upstream v2.1.0:

1. `fractionalBits` is read from the file and used as a shift exponent with no
   upper bound. Versions 2 and 3 store each coordinate as a signed 24-bit
   fixed-point integer, so at most 23 bits can be fractional (one bit is the
   sign). A crafted header declaring more produces an out-of-range shift and a
   meaningless scale factor.

2. `invSigmoid` maps the packed alpha byte back to a logit. Packed alpha uses the
   full uint8 range, so bytes 0 and 255 land exactly on probability 0 and 1, whose
   logits are -inf and +inf. A decoded cloud then carries non-finite opacity, and
   a default opacity of 1.0 round-trips to byte 255 and comes back infinite —
   meaning the *common* case, not just a hostile one, produces invalid data.

Both are clamped with a named epsilon matching Melkor's own logit contract, so the
two implementations cannot disagree about what a valid opacity is.

Upstream status: not submitted. Both are candidates for upstream; file them when the
dependency is upgraded to v3.0.0/format v4 under P0-09.

Applies to: nianticlabs/spz @ 2cf0be04d86b5f9632d9073ccbbe3b1e6a609f31 (v2.1.0)

